refine the following rebuttal, making it clear, sound, and easy to follow: \textbf{1. Novelty \& Comparison to MLA and TransMLA.}
We give a first universal solution to convert mainstream attentions (e.g. MHA, MQA, GQA, etc.) of MLLMs into MLA forms for multimodal understanding regardless their topologies or newly incorporated components. Taking Qwen3 as an example, it introduces QK-Norm in its GQA, making TransMLA or related methods barely work, while we successfully transform \textbf{Qwen3-VL} into MLA variant. On VideoMME, our compressed model achieves \textbf{69.74}, surpassing the baseline's \textbf{68.89}.
Even for MLLMs using MLA as attentions, considering the mainstream ViTs still use non-MLA attentions, our solution can handle its position encodings and adjust latent dimensions for better performance-effiency trade-offs. Specifically, our Modality-Aware Adapters and Visual Latent Budgeting solve the multimodal information migration challenge, enabling highly compact latent representations. This efficiency allows us to reinvest the memory savings to expand the effective head dimension, significantly enhancing model expressivity. Consequently, our method acts as a robust upgrade kit for the community.

refine the rebuttal, making it clear, sound, and easy to follow: Regarding ``fine-grained spatial or temporal reasoning'', we empricially demonstrate that our method retains or even improves the fine-grained perception of its uncompressed baseline:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Temporal Precision (Charades-STA):} Our method notably \textbf{improves} temporal grounding performance (Table 2: R@0.5 $\uparrow$ \textbf{5.3\%}, mIoU $\uparrow$ \textbf{3.7\%}). This proves that our latent compression effectively exploit redundancy to sharpen temporal boundaries rather than harming them.
    \item \textbf{Spatial Detail (MVBench):} On this fine-grained perception benchmark, we strictly match the baseline (74.3 vs 74.4), no loss in event/action recognition.
    \item \textbf{Extreme Context (NIAH):} For ``extreme settings," our Needle-in-a-Haystack test (Supp. Fig. 1) retains 94.2\% accuracy, verifying robustness.
\end{itemize}

refine the rebuttal, making it clear, sound, and easy to follow, no structures: Note MLA is designed to maximize \textbf{compute density}, unleashing higher throughput of GPUs by shrinking the KV cache, thereby cutting memory I/O.
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Throughput \& Capacity:} Long-context inference is predominantly constrained by \textbf{Memory Bandwidth (I/O)}. By compressing the KV cache (approx. $2\times$ reduction, Table 1), we significantly reduce memory I/O demands. This reduction directly translates to \textbf{higher throughput} (e.g., via larger batch sizes) and, crucially, supports the \textbf{expanded context capacity} explored in our paper.
    \item \textbf{Negligible Cost:} The additional FLOPs from our linear adapters ($O(d^2)$) are negligible ($<1\%$) compared to the quadratic complexity of Attention ($O(T^2)$), ensuring no meaningful latency penalty.
\end{itemize}
